      "\n   - The integral becomes `∑_{i,j} L(e_i) L(e_j) ∫ a_i a_j d(product measure)`.\n   - The product measure is such that `∫ a_i a_j d(product measure) = 1 if i=j else 0`.\n\n4. **Simplify**:\n   - The integral becomes `∑_{i} L(e_i)²`.\n\n#### Possible Lean Lemmas Needed\n\n1. **Integrating `(∑ c_i a_i)²`**:\n   - If we could prove that `∫ a : Fin n → ℝ, (∑ c_i a_i)² d(product Gaussian) = ∑ c_i²`, then we could directly apply it.\n   - The proof of this lemma would require:\n     - Expanding the square.\n     - Using Fubini to split the integral into `i,j` parts.\n     - Noting that `∫ a_i a_j = 0` if `i≠j`.\n\nBut perhaps we can avoid this by building it directly:\n\n- The function `a ↦ (∑ c_i a_i)²` can be expanded as `∑_{i,j} c_i c_j a_i a_j`.\n- Integration gives `∑_{i,j} c_i c_j ∫ a_i a_j`.\n- But `∫ a_i a_j = 0` if `i ≠ j`, otherwise it's `1`.\n- So it's `∑_i c_i²`.\n\n### Proof in Lean\n\nLooking at the sorries in the Lean code, the missing piece is the actual proof of `variance_dual_stdGaussianMulti`. \n\n#### Formal Proof Sketch for `variance_dual_stdGaussianMulti`\n\n1. **Use the definition of variance**:\n   - Since `E[L] = 0` by `isCentered_stdGaussianMulti`, `Var(L) = E[L²]`.\n\n2. **Compute `E[L²]`**:\n   - Use the mapping property to write it as an integral over the product space.\n   - Expand `(∑ a_i L(e_i))²`.\n   - Use independence to simplify the integral.\n\n3. **Conclusion**:\n   - Obtain `∑ L(e_i)²`.\n\nHowever, Lean doesn't have a direct lemma for `E[(∑ c_i a_i)²] = ∑ c_i²`, so perhaps we can use the fact that for the product measure, `∫ (∑ c_i a_i)² = ∑ c_i²`, and in our case `a_i` are independent Gaussians.\n\nBut actually, we don't even have independence encoded in `Measure.pi`, because in Lean, `Measure.pi` just constructs a product measure without assuming independence of the coordinates. \n\nHowever, for a product measure, we do have that `∫ (a : ι → ℝ), f a i * g a j ∂(Measure.pi μ) = (∫ x, f x ∂μ i) * (∫ x, g x ∂μ j)` if `i ≠ j`, because we can split the integral into `i` and `j` parts.\n\nBut maybe we can use `Measure.pi` directly and expand:\n\n`(∑ i, c_i a_i)^2 = ∑_{i,j} c_i c_j a_i a_j`.\n\nThen:\n\n`∫ (∑ i, c_i a_i)^2 ∂(Measure.pi (fun _ ↦ Gaussian 0 1))\n  = ∑_{i,j} c_i c_j ∫ a_i a_j ∂(Measure.pi (fun _ ↦ Gaussian 0 1))`.\n\nBut:\n\n`∫ a_i a_j ∂(Measure.pi (fun _ ↦ Gaussian 0 1)) = if i = j then 1 else 0`.\n\nThus, the expression becomes `∑_{i} c_i²`.\n\nHowever, we need to formalize why `∫ a_i a_j = δ_{i,j}`.\n\n1. If `i = j`, then `∫ a_i² = 1` (since it's standard Gaussian).\n2. If `i ≠ j`, then the integral splits as `(∫",
      "\n  have h₁ : (stdGaussianMulti E).charFun = fun t ↦\n      Real.exp (- (t ∘ L) ^ 2 / 2) := by sorry\n  have h₂ : Var[L; stdGaussianMulti E] = ∑ i, L (stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i) ^ 2 := by sorry\n  exact h₂",
      "\n  have h₁ : (stdGaussianMulti E).isProbability := inferInstance\n  have h₂ : E = E := rfl\n  have h₃ : (L : E →L[ℝ] ℝ) = L := rfl\n  -- Calculate the variance directly using the properties of the Gaussian distribution\n  simp_all [variance, isCentered_stdGaussianMulti, stdGaussianMulti, Finset.sum_range_succ, mul_comm]\n  <;>\n  simp_all [sub_eq_add_neg, add_assoc]\n  <;>\n  norm_num\n  <;>\n  ring_nf\n  <;>\n  simp_all [integral_ab]\n  <;>\n  linarith",
      "\n  have h1 : Var[L; stdGaussianMulti E] = ∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), (L (stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i)) ^ 2 := by\n    rw [Var, isCentered_stdGaussianMulti]\n    have h2 : (L : E → ℝ) ∘ (fun x : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E) → ℝ => ∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), x i • stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i)\n      = fun x : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E) → ℝ => ∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), x i * L (stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i) := by\n      funext x\n      calc\n        (L : E → ℝ) ∘ (fun x : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E) → ℝ => ∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), x i • stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i) x\n          = L (∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), x i • stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i) := rfl\n        _ = ∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), x i * L (stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i) := by\n          calc\n            L (∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), x i • stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i)\n              = ∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), L (x i • stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i) := by\n                apply L.map_sum\n              _ = ∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), x i * L (stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i) := by\n                apply Finset.sum_congr rfl\n                intro i _\n                simp [L.map_smul, Real.linearMap_smul_left]\n    rw [h2]\n    have h3 : (Measure.pi (fun _ : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E) => gaussianReal 0 1)).map (fun x : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E) → ℝ => ∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), x i * L (stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i))\n      = (Measure.pi (fun _ : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E) => gaussianReal 0 1)).map (fun x : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E) → ℝ => ∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), x i * L (stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i)) := rfl\n    rw [show (Measure.pi (fun _ : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E) => gaussianReal 0 1)).map (fun x : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E) → ℝ => ∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), x i * L (stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i))\n        = (Measure.pi (fun _ : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E) => gaussianReal 0 1)).map (fun x : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E) => ℝ => ∑ i : Fin (Module.finrank ℝ E), x i * L (stdOrthonormalBasis ℝ E i